<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="102" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6627847" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6627847" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6627847/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="102" targetBox="[164,757,305,720]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[779,1371,307,726]" pageId="3" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[780,956,307,332]" pageId="3" pageNumber="102">Distribution.</emphasis>
E Brazilian Amazon, limited in N by Amazon River, in W by Rio Madeira, and in E by Rio Xingu; S limit is unknown.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="102" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[779,1371,307,726]" pageId="3" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[780,1040,456,489]" pageId="3" pageNumber="102">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
No specific data are available. Dorsal color of the Xingu Silky Anteater is gray, rump is yellow, venter is pale yellowish, and legs and tail are gray. Dorsalstripe is evident, and ventral stripe is indistinct and irregular. Fronto-nasal region of skull is not depressed, giving a
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[164,1370,736,1238]" pageId="3" pageNumber="102">straight profile. External aperture of ear is directed laterally. Naso-maxillary sutures are about parallel to each other, with wide fronto-maxillary suture. Fronto-parietalis triangular, and pterygoid bone overlaps tympanic bulla.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
